:::summary
Aristotle (384–322 BC) was a Greek philosopher and polymath — student of Plato, tutor of Alexander the Great, and founder of the Lyceum. He made foundational contributions to logic, metaphysics, ethics, biology, physics, rhetoric, and poetics. His systematic approach to knowledge and his concept of *eudaimonia* (human flourishing) have profoundly shaped Western philosophy, science, and theology.
:::

